															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/thedeadlymoose" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(732274); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=732274&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164255" alt="thedeadlymoose" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=732274)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/thedeadlymoose" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(732274); return false;" >thedeadlymoose</a></span> <span class="odate time_1405018487 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">10 Jul 2014 18:54</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2067053">
									

<p>Two things to address:</p>
<p>Singular 'they' <em>is</em> the acceptable gender-neutral pronoun in English; it only fell out of favor in recent years due to attempts to make English conform to Latin rules and a backlash against feminist thought a few decades ago (but mainly, the Latin rules thing; see also split infinitives).</p>
<p>It's come back into favor rather recently, partly due to the rise of more people coming out of the closet as genderqueer and embracing those pronouns for themselves.</p>
<p>It's awkward in the sense that people aren't used to it, but it does stop being awkward when you're used to it (in most cases).</p>
<p>However, as for the <em>article's</em> concern&#8212;</p>
<p>Within the article itself, it's meant to imply that the Hand see &quot;Summer's Exile&quot; as a person who would properly be referred to this way, albeit a person who is a predator. (As opposed to <a href="/the-second-child">017</a>, who they see as a straight-up scary monster, an Other Thing, and they're frightened of even TRYING to guess its gender, partly because of the taboo.)</p>
<p>However, I don't know that the rest of the article gets that across successfully; while I'm very happy with the present form of the article, I will be tweaking that post-contest.</p>
<p>If it's easier, I <em>may</em> end up changing the pronouns to &quot;she/her&quot; and save the singular &quot;they&quot; for an article that's about &#8230; well, an actually humanoid person who is actually genderqueer, so it's only as confusing as it has to be.</p>

							</div>

								
